other people to say those
things.

13:35.048 --> 13:36.983 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I think that's my biggest
fear.

13:37.016 --> 13:38.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ZACK BRADLEY, Student: My
concern is war.

13:38.785 --> 13:40.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But that's a concern with any
candidate.

13:40.486 --> 13:43.022 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With Hillary, it was going to be
war with
Russia.

13:43.056 --> 13:45.792 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
With Trump, it's going to be a
civil war.

13:45.825 --> 13:47.994 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the question is, who is
going to win either
of those?

13:48.027 --> 13:54.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KATIE ONTIVEROS, Student: Seeing
that my generation
doesn't want to take action or
take responsibility

13:54.500 --> 14:03.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for their future and my future,
our future,
I just don't want to stay in a
country like

14:03.843 --> 14:05.745 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this, if that's what it's going
to be like.

14:05.778 --> 14:08.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KEALA NAIPO, Student: There is
no doubt that
the president election was a
huge shock to

14:08.981 --> 14:10.416 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
me.

14:10.450 --> 14:13.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I call our citizens to have
some respect
and faith in our country.

14:13.619 --> 14:17.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have made it through a civil
war, two world
wars, the Great Depression, and
terrorist

14:17.623 --> 14:18.591 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
attacks.

14:18.624 --> 14:19.592 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But this is no fight.

14:19.625 --> 14:20.793 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We elected someone new as
president.

14:20.827 --> 14:21.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That shouldn't be tearing us
apart.

14:21.894 --> 14:23.629 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It should be bringing us
together.

14:23.663 --> 14:27.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For a closer
look now, we
turn to Kavitha Cardoza of
Education Week,

14:27.166 --> 14:31.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who has been talking to teachers
across the
country, and Mariama Richards,
an administrator

14:31.037 --> 14:33.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at Friends Central School just
outside of
Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.

14:33.806 --> 14:35.408 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Kavitha, let me start with you.

14:35.441 --> 14:37.510 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What have you found in your
reporting in the
past couple days?

14:37.543 --> 14:41.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA, Education Week:
Well, this
is something that teachers are
used to.

14:41.280 --> 14:45.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have been dealing with
these emotions
through the campaign season.

14:45.685 --> 14:49.922 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The election results just made
it more concrete.

14:49.956 --> 14:52.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Children in schools are just a
microcosm of
society.

14:52.759 --> 14:57.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so they're not surprised at
all that some
of these emotions are spilling
into the classroom.

14:57.096 --> 15:00.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, are these
the students'
own opinions, or are they
parroting what their

15:00.867 --> 15:01.901 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
parents say at home?

15:01.934 --> 15:03.770 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: I think a bit
of both.

15:03.803 --> 15:09.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With the teenagers we just saw,
some of it
is their own, because they are
reading newspapers

15:09.342 --> 15:11.878 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and watching the television
themselves.

15:11.911 --> 15:18.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I spoke to a teacher in
California, and
she teaches pre-K, and she says
children just

15:18.084 --> 15:20.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
absorb the stress of their
parents.

15:20.920 --> 15:27.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so she teaches in a very
diverse community,
a lot of Muslims, a lot of
immigrants.

15:27.426 --> 15:31.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And she said she has noticed
that the children
are more aggressive, they're
more prone to

15:31.898 --> 15:33.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
crying, very emotional.

15:33.866 --> 15:38.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So she and other teachers have
actually put
the learning, the academic goals
on hold with

15:38.471 --> 15:41.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
these children and they have
said, you know
what?

15:41.073 --> 15:47.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's create our own curriculum,
how to be
a good friend, how to listen,
how to be calm

15:47.313 --> 15:49.048 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
when you feel upset.

15:49.081 --> 15:53.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She said a lot of the parents
are stressed
about maybe their families being
split up,

15:53.886 --> 15:57.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
maybe losing health care if
Obamacare goes
away.

15:57.089 --> 16:02.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Mariama
Richards, what kind
of things are you grappling with
at your school

16:02.228 --> 16:04.030 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or the teachers have been coming
to you with?

16:04.063 --> 16:06.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARIAMA RICHARDS, Friends
Central School:
One of the biggest issues that
is in front

16:06.799 --> 16:13.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of us right now is a community
that wants
to see change happen, that felt
really connected

16:13.673 --> 16:20.012 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to the election season,
regardless of which
side that particular student or
family was

16:20.046 --> 16:21.814 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
on.

16:21.848 --> 16:25.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now they're grappling with
kind of how
do they push through some of the
values that

16:25.585 --> 16:31.123 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
they really do love and
appreciate about the
community that they're building
and finding

16:31.157 --> 16:34.060 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
that there's a split in
perspective on how
to move forward.

16:34.093 --> 16:39.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For example, there are students
who feel so
angry and upset now, that it's
hard for them

16:39.665 --> 16:45.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to think about engaging those
who may have
voted for our current
president-elect, because

16:45.538 --> 16:50.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they see that engagement as
people who think
less of them, who don't think
that they're

16:50.743 --> 16:55.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
full human beings, while there
are other students
who may not necessarily be on
the side of

16:55.047 --> 16:59.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the president-elect as well, but
they're in
a position where they feel like
this is an

16:59.185 --> 17:02.722 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
opportunity for us to learn what
the other
side of the world is thinking.

17:02.755 --> 17:09.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so even in places where you
have commonalities
in terms of goals, we're still
seeing students

17:09.095 --> 17:13.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
really struggle with kind of,
what's our best
case forward moving forward?

17:13.566 --> 17:18.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With the little ones, they are
struggling
with very similar things that we
just heard,

17:18.271 --> 17:19.906 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
fear.

17:19.939 --> 17:23.843 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They are hearing lots of
information and not
understanding the context for
it.

17:23.876 --> 17:30.249 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And we see it play out
definitely in the classroom
setting in how they're
connecting with others,

17:30.283 --> 17:34.353 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
whether or not they feel
reserved, whether
or not they feel fear.

17:34.387 --> 17:38.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we are, as teachers, trying
to support
them in the process of getting
through that.

17:38.457 --> 17:44.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Kavitha
Cardoza, are the
teachers saying, in essence,
what the children

17:44.196 --> 17:45.998 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are feeling?

17:46.032 --> 17:50.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, is there a collective
sense of anxiety
or tension, whether --
regardless- of which

17:50.536 --> 17:52.605 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
side of the election they came
down on?

17:52.638 --> 17:57.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: I think the
teachers are
really, really making a
concerted effort to,

17:57.877 --> 18:02.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
no matter what their personal
beliefs, to
be that oasis of calm for the
children and

18:02.848 --> 18:05.251 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to kind of bring everyone
together.

18:05.284 --> 18:10.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are students who, for
example, supported
climate change, and they are
devastated, we

18:10.456 --> 18:12.224 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have heard reports.

18:12.258 --> 18:17.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are students -- I spoke to
a teacher
in Ohio, and she said her
students came with

18:17.396 --> 18:22.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump T-shirts and the "Make
America Great
Again" caps, and they were
thrilled.

18:22.101 --> 18:26.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so within these schools and
within all
the children, they teach how do
you make it

18:26.973 --> 18:30.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
safe and calm and respectful,
really?

18:30.343 --> 18:36.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Mariama
Richards, you took
steps to prepare parents before
the election.

18:36.749 --> 18:38.617 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What are you hearing from them
now?

18:38.651 --> 18:41.921 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARIAMA RICHARDS: After the
election, we have
been in constant communication,
which I think

18:41.954 --> 18:45.691 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
is really key to that
partnership with families.

18:45.725 --> 18:49.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the letters we have sent
home have included
additional links for support.

18:49.762 --> 18:54.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in some cases, we have
parents who really
want us to move away and say,
OK, it's over.

18:54.500 --> 18:58.671 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's now move on with the
practice of going
to school and doing the work.

18:58.704 --> 19:03.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are other families
that are so ultimately
grateful that we're taking that
time to be

19:03.876 --> 19:06.645 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
able to help their children
through this process.

19:06.679 --> 19:11.350 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think what we have
learned, as a Quaker
school that's embedded in the
value-centered

19:11.384 --> 19:16.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
curriculum, is that we know, if
students do
not feel affirmed, they actually
won't learn.

19:16.989 --> 19:22.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We won't be able to teach math
if they feel
scared and if they feel like
they are at risk.

19:22.161 --> 19:26.499 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so we have to be able to
find a wonderful
balance of incorporating both of
those in

19:26.532 --> 19:28.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the classroom setting.

19:28.401 --> 19:32.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Kavitha
Cardoza, we have
been seeing such an increase on
every educational

19:32.938 --> 19:38.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
level, from middle schools to
high school
to colleges, of acts of
intimidation, bullying,

19:38.711 --> 19:42.214 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
swastikas spray-painted here and
there.

19:42.248 --> 19:43.482 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What are you seeing in your
reporting?

19:43.516 --> 19:46.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: A lot more,
Hari.

19:46.719 --> 19:50.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One is that these kids share,
tape everything
and share everything on social
media, so it's

19:50.990 --> 19:53.926 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
much more accessible.

19:53.959 --> 19:59.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think just today on my Twitter
feed, I saw
someone say: My daughter came
home from school

19:59.732 --> 20:04.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and said she heard that she no
longer has
to be politically correct.

20:04.470 --> 20:09.308 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so you're seeing a lot of
things which
kids, some of them don't even
know what the

20:09.341 --> 20:11.510 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
implications are and what it
means.

20:11.544 --> 20:17.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But because it's being shared so
widely, kids,
you know, just copy sometimes.

20:17.349 --> 20:18.751 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Yes.

20:18.784 --> 20:21.153 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Kavitha Cardoza, Mariama
Richards, thank you
both.

20:21.187 --> 20:26.392 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: Thank you,
Hari.

20:26.425 --> 20:35.601 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARIAMA RICHARDS: Thank you.

20:35.634 --> 20:44.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: On this Veterans
Day, we turn
to what a Trump administration
might mean

20:44.210 --> 20:46.445 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for those who have served our
country.

20:46.479 --> 20:52.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On Election Day, 61 percent of
veterans voted
for Mr. Trump, 34 percent voted
for Secretary

20:52.852 --> 20:54.286 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Clinton.

20:54.320 --> 20:58.424 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of non-veterans, 45 percent
voted Trump, while
half voted for Clinton.

20:58.457 --> 21:02.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what do vets expect a
President Trump
to do?

21:02.228 --> 21:03.963 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham has more.

21:03.996 --> 21:08.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Candidate
Trump repeatedly
expressed support for those who
served in

21:08.200 --> 21:11.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the U.S. armed forces, and it
showed in the
results on Election Day.

21:11.837 --> 21:16.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he also angered many with
his denigration
of Senator John McCain and of
the Khan family,

21:16.775 --> 21:19.011 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
whose son died fighting in Iraq.

21:19.044 --> 21:23.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on what veterans might
want from
a Trump administration, I'm
joined by Paul

21:23.449 --> 21:28.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rieckhoff, executive director of
Iraq and
Afghanistan Veterans of America.

21:28.554 --> 21:34.627 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Paul Rieckhoff, as you saw,
Trump was chosen
by veterans 2-1 over Clinton.

21:34.660 --> 21:36.395 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Why do you think that is?

21:36.428 --> 21:38.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL RIECKHOFF, Founder &amp;
Executive Director,
Iraq and Afghanistan Veterans of
America:

21:38.197 --> 21:41.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, I think we have got to
start by being
careful about overgeneralizing
veterans.

21:41.600 --> 21:45.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are 22 million in America,
and they
represent a very large group,
but they're

21:45.771 --> 21:47.573 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
really not a bloc.

21:47.606 --> 21:53.345 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If you look at the older
veterans, about 18
million or so that haven't
served since 9/11,

21:53.379 --> 21:55.514 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they tend to be mostly male.

21:55.548 --> 21:57.516 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They tend to be more white than
the general
population.

21:57.550 --> 22:02.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, really, what some of that is
just a reflection
of the demographics that
supported Trump vs.

22:02.121 --> 22:03.422 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Clinton.

22:03.455 --> 22:05.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the younger generation,
they're about
20 percent female.

22:05.858 --> 22:07.459 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're much more ethnically
diverse.

22:07.493 --> 22:09.361 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I think we see some more
political diversity
there.

22:09.395 --> 22:13.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think what you do see is a
frustration
with the status quo.

22:13.966 --> 22:17.236 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You see some frustration with
the bureaucracy
in Washington.

22:17.269 --> 22:19.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You see a certain group of folks
who just
don't like Hillary Clinton.

22:19.972 --> 22:25.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that's a very real
problem, just not
in the veterans community, but
more broadly.

22:25.611 --> 22:27.780 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And you see folks that respond
to rhetoric.

22:27.813 --> 22:29.949 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Donald Trump talked a big game
on veterans.

22:29.982 --> 22:33.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He said it over and over again:
I'm going
to take care of the vets, I'm
going to take

22:33.085 --> 22:34.887 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
care of the vets.

22:34.920 --> 22:38.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Their policies at times were not
that different,
but his rhetoric was much more
aggressive.

22:38.490 --> 22:40.693 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And it's a populist issue.

22:40.726 --> 22:44.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People responded to that and
many people believe
that's what he's going to do.

22:44.730 --> 22:49.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's been a campaign platform
that he's really
focused on.

22:49.268 --> 22:51.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now we're going to try to hold
him accountable
as he becomes president.

22:51.637 --> 22:56.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If it's going to be a capstone
of his presidency,
it is going to be a very hard
series of things

22:56.108 --> 22:57.876 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to accomplish.

22:57.910 --> 23:00.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Every president says he is going
to fix the
VA, and most of them leave
without it getting

23:00.813 --> 23:02.581 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
done.

23:02.615 --> 23:04.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, let's say
you're pulled
into the room and you're asked
to counsel

23:04.183 --> 23:06.485 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
him on policy with regards to
veterans.

23:06.518 --> 23:08.287 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What's priority one for you?

23:08.320 --> 23:14.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL RIECKHOFF: I think priority
one is to
establish a real strong
leadership group within

23:14.526 --> 23:19.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Washington that is going to make
veterans
at the hub, and not just the VA
at the hub.

23:19.265 --> 23:23.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our conversation over the last
two years,
especially after the VA scandal,
has been

23:23.435 --> 23:25.237 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
only really framed around the
VA.

23:25.271 --> 23:28.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I think there is an epic
opportunity to be
able to open this conversation
to involve

23:28.907 --> 23:33.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
philanthropy, involve the
private sector,
the medical community,
universities.

23:33.379 --> 23:35.247 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Government can't be the only
solution here.

23:35.281 --> 23:39.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We see it in some of the members
who come
to us in most urgent need; 70
percent are

23:39.351 --> 23:41.120 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
not enrolled in the VA.

23:41.153 --> 23:44.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, we do need to improve the
VA, but we
have got to have a true veteran
strategy that

23:44.890 --> 23:47.660 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
expands beyond government.

23:47.693 --> 23:49.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President Obama has never really
laid that
out.

23:50.029 --> 23:54.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We attacked the VA problem after
the scandal
and we heard a lot of good talk
from Congress,

23:54.300 --> 23:59.338 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
but there was never
comprehensive strategy,
after we engaged in multiple
wars, to actually

23:59.371 --> 24:00.339 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
care for people coming home.

24:00.372 --> 24:01.807 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So we have got to clear goals.

24:01.840 --> 24:02.908 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We have got to have a strategy.

24:02.941 --> 24:04.276 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we need to have the right
team in place.

24:04.310 --> 24:08.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is an opportunity to bring
together a
bipartisan coalition.

24:08.213 --> 24:12.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It might be the only political
issue we can
get Republicans and Democrats
behind together.

24:12.451 --> 24:16.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, for any president,
it would be
a smart issue to come out in the
first year

24:17.022 --> 24:18.791 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in such a divisive time.

24:18.824 --> 24:22.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Another issue
that's obviously
very, very troubling is the rate
of suicide

24:22.695 --> 24:26.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
among veterans, something like
20 a day, I
believe.

24:26.365 --> 24:31.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What can a president, what can a
presidential
administration do to address
that horrendous

24:31.637 --> 24:33.372 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
issue?

24:33.405 --> 24:35.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL RIECKHOFF: Well, I think we
have seen
President Obama make tremendous
progress on

24:36.008 --> 24:37.843 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
this in simply talking about it.

24:37.876 --> 24:43.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Veterans advocacy groups like
IAVA and others
have been really screaming for
years for help

24:43.048 --> 24:48.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to try to explain that we're
losing our brothers
and sisters to our left and
right tragically

24:48.287 --> 24:50.622 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to suicide on a daily basis.

24:50.656 --> 24:55.160 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We had a day last year we had
seven suicide
calls to IAVA in one day alone.

24:55.194 --> 24:57.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think it does start with
prioritizing
it.

24:57.563 --> 25:01.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It also starts with
understanding that it's
not just a veterans issue or a
government

25:01.066 --> 25:02.101 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
issue.

25:02.134 --> 25:03.369 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a national health priority.

25:03.402 --> 25:05.504 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And we have got to rally
resources around
that.

25:05.537 --> 25:09.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when veterans do come
forward and they
overcome the stigma and they
respond to that

25:09.274 --> 25:11.009 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
rhetoric, the help has got to be
there.

25:11.043 --> 25:12.311 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we have seen wait times.

25:12.344 --> 25:14.113 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We have seen bureaucracies.

25:14.146 --> 25:18.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even the Veterans Crisis Line,
which has been
great, struggled at times to
keep up with

25:18.217 --> 25:20.185 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the demand.

25:20.219 --> 25:23.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if those veterans are brave
and are courageous
and are encouraged to come
forward, the resources

25:23.155 --> 25:24.690 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have got to be there.

25:24.723 --> 25:26.959 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we have got a critical
shortage of quality
mental health care workers.

25:26.992 --> 25:31.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One thing IAVA has called on
President Obama
to do and will call on President
Trump to

25:31.463 --> 25:36.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
do is to issue a national call
to service
for people who are qualified
mental health

25:36.535 --> 25:39.905 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to serve, to serve in the VA, at
the DOD,
in private nonprofits.

25:39.938 --> 25:45.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We need an army of mental health
care workers
to support this flood of need
that is coming

25:45.077 --> 25:49.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
home, not just after our wars in
Iraq and
Afghanistan, but after decades
and decades

25:49.515 --> 25:51.350 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of veterans who have
underserved.

25:51.383 --> 25:54.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many are the veterans that we're
losing to
suicide are Vietnam veterans who
were never

25:54.787 --> 25:55.954 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
properly cared for.

25:55.988 --> 25:57.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Paul Rieckhoff,
thank you.

25:57.156 --> 26:04.463 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL RIECKHOFF: Thank you, sir.

26:04.496 --> 26:14.206 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we come back
to the analysis
of Shields and Brooks.

26:14.239 --> 26:18.677 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's syndicated columnist Mark
Shields and
New York Times columnist David
Brooks.

26:18.710 --> 26:22.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And let me just kick this off by
saying there's
nobody I would rather spend more
than nine

26:22.681 --> 26:24.416 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hours with on election night
than the two
of you.

26:24.450 --> 26:25.417 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

26:25.451 --> 26:26.618 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Thank you so much,
Judy.

26:26.652 --> 26:27.886 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

26:27.920 --> 26:31.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, having said
that, political
earthquake.

26:31.089 --> 26:33.459 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The earth moved under our feet,
David.

26:33.492 --> 26:35.260 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How big an earthquake was it?

26:35.294 --> 26:38.997 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, it's
certainly the political
shock of our lives, at least my
lifetime.

26:39.031 --> 26:43.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It feels like almost the '60s,
sort of like
political revolution, cultural
revolution,

26:44.002 --> 26:49.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
aesthetic revolution, the things
that now
you can say and get elected
president.

26:49.842 --> 26:51.710 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And so it was all those things.

26:51.743 --> 26:56.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm sort of finding myself in a
strange emotional
territory, if I could lie on the
couch here.

26:56.515 --> 26:57.916 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
On the one hand, Trump appalls
me.

26:57.950 --> 27:01.019 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I won't be shy about that.

27:01.053 --> 27:06.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But having -- with the elective
democratic
process having taken its turn, I
sort of feel

27:06.825 --> 27:11.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we have to owe some respect to
the process
and owe some respect to the
electorate and

27:11.930 --> 27:16.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the people who voted him, on the
assumption
that they have something to
teach us.

27:16.034 --> 27:18.136 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so all these people are
marching in the
street.

27:18.170 --> 27:20.005 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There is all this hostility.

27:20.038 --> 27:23.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I find myself -- and I think
this was the
president's attitude and frankly
Hillary Clinton's

27:23.141 --> 27:25.777 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
attitude -- of respectful pause.

27:25.811 --> 27:30.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Maybe I will be as upset at
Trump as I was
in another week, but what do
they try to teach

27:31.016 --> 27:32.184 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
us?

27:32.217 --> 27:33.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Just try to understand what the
situation
we're in is.

27:33.452 --> 27:35.187 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Respectful pause,
Mark?

27:35.220 --> 27:36.955 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

27:36.989 --> 27:42.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I, Judy, believe devoutly that
the national
election is the closest thing we
have to a

27:42.361 --> 27:45.097 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
civic sacrament of democracy.

27:45.130 --> 27:53.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I really do think that heed
must be paid,
and when people make a decision,
those who

27:53.805 --> 28:00.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are on the other side, including
me, accept
it, for that reason.

28:00.345 --> 28:06.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that probably the best
analysis, of
the millions of words that were
written, other

28:06.785 --> 28:11.657 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than David's -- David's were
really perceptive
and wise.

28:11.690 --> 28:18.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there's a woman named -- I
don't know
her name -- Salena Zito at
"Atlantic."

28:18.730 --> 28:20.532 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And she said something.

28:20.566 --> 28:28.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She said, to understand this
election, critics
of Donald Trump take him
literally, but not

28:28.574 --> 28:30.309 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
seriously.

28:30.342 --> 28:33.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
His supporters take him
seriously, but not
literally.

28:33.512 --> 28:41.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In other words, so while his
critics were
very upset with what he said,
the -- his supporters

28:41.286 --> 28:48.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really were the mood and the
positions he
took, rather than precise
phrases or words.

28:48.760 --> 28:53.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I say that because now, as of
Tuesday, everyone
has to take him seriously, and I
think that's

28:53.098 --> 28:55.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
what we're seeing.

28:55.067 --> 29:03.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the anxiety in schools
that we hear,
in minority communities, those
with the archbishop

29:03.275 --> 29:09.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Los Angeles at Our Lady of
the Saints Cathedral
yesterday at an interfaith
service with Jewish

29:09.748 --> 29:16.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and Muslim, and was very open
and said, our
children are fearful that their
parents -- the

29:16.421 --> 29:18.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
government is going to come and
take their
parents away.

29:18.924 --> 29:22.527 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think that's a consequence
of the election.

